# Git and PR Conventions

## Branch naming

All APEX-driven feature branches use:

```
feat/apex-<featureAdoId>-<slug>
```

- `<featureAdoId>` — the ADO Feature work item id (e.g. `42`)
- `<slug>` — short kebab-case title derived from the Feature title (max 40 chars, lowercase, alphanumeric + hyphens, no special characters)

Example: `feat/apex-42-shift-scheduler-widget`

Never commit directly to `main`.

## Commit messages

Use the [Conventional Commits](https://www.conventionalcommits.org/) format:

```
<type>(<scope>): <short summary — imperative mood, no period>

<optional body: why, not what>
```

Types: `feat`, `fix`, `refactor`, `test`, `chore`, `docs`, `style`, `perf`

For APEX-driven features always include the ADO reference in the body:

```
feat(shift-scheduler): add ShiftSchedulerWidget component

Implements APEX-approved design doc for ADO Feature #42.
- Add ShiftSchedulerWidget with availability grid
- Add useShiftScheduler hook with TanStack Query
- Add unit tests for component and hook
```

## Commit hygiene

- Run `git add -A` then inspect `git status` before committing — confirm only intended files are staged
- Never stage `.env`, `.env.local`, or any file containing secrets or API keys
- Never stage generated artefacts (build output, `dist/`, `node_modules/`)
- Never use `--no-verify` to skip hooks

## Pushing

```bash
git push -u origin HEAD
```

Use `-u` on the first push for a new branch to set the upstream. If the push is rejected (non-fast-forward), run `git pull --rebase` then push again. Never force-push (`--force`).

## Pull request

- Title: matches the commit summary line
- Body: reference the ADO Feature with `AB#<featureAdoId>` so Azure Boards auto-links the PR
- Base branch: `main`
- Include a brief test plan section listing which tests were added or modified

After creating the PR, update the ADO Feature state to "In Pull Request" and attach the PR URL as a hyperlink on the work item.

## Guardrails

- Never open a PR from `main` into `main`
- Never force-push to any branch
- Never merge without a PR (direct pushes to `main` are blocked)
